{
  "texts": [
    "By defining it in Recital 55 and outlining specific provisions in Articles 14 and 17, a foundation for identifying and addressing this controversial practice is provided.",
    "The regulation aims to hold platforms accountable for their content moderation actions and enhance transparency by providing users with information about why certain content is affected [157].",
    "Yet the DSA adopts a particular definition of shadow banning referring to accounts being secretely suspended, rather than the more modern interpretation of secret visibility reductions, such as lower social media posts viewing [108].",
    "This lack of adoption of a more up-to-date interpretation of shadow-banning ought to be kept in mind, from a legal standpoint, while differentiating different types of visibility reductions.",
    "Moreover, the complexities surrounding the detection and proof of shadow banning practices may make it more challenging to enforce than other forms of content moderation, such as tackling false information."
  ]
}